data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

Your code only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET Framework → .NET 8 migration. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. There are no calls to `Thread.Abort`, `Thread.Interrupt`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or catches of `ThreadAbortException`.

This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

---

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort):

You could simplify with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run`, but that's a design choice, not a migration requirement:

```csharp
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

⚠️ Also note the **closure-over-loop-variable** bug in your original code — `item` is captured by reference, so all threads may process the last item. The `Parallel.ForEach` version avoids this.
